<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="29" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="29">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Cryptantha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cryptantha subamplexicaulis" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subamplexicaulis">Cryptantha subamplexicaulis</taxonomicName>
≡ 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Eritrichium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eritrichium subamplexicaule" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subamplexicaule">Eritrichium subamplexicaule</taxonomicName>
Phil., Fl. Atacam. 39. 1860. Type: Chile. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Región">Region</normalizedToken>
de Antofagasta: Paposo, Dec. 1853, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">R.A. Philippi s.n.</emphasis>
(lectotype, designated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Johnston, IM" journalOrPublisher="Contributions from the Gray Herbarium of Harvard University" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 118" refId="B16" refString="Johnston, IM, 1927. Studies in the Boraginaceae VI. A revision of the South American Boraginoideae. Contributions from the Gray Herbarium of Harvard University 78: 1 - 118" title="Studies in the Boraginaceae VI. A revision of the South American Boraginoideae." volume="78" year="1927">Johnston 1927</bibRefCitation>
, pg. 41: SGO [SGO000004139 digital image!]; isolectotypes: GH [GH00096579 digital image!], HAL [HAL0115278 digital image!]).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="29" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="29">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="29">
In the protologue of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Eritrichium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eritrichium subamplexicule" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subamplexicule">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="29">Eritrichium subamplexicule</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.162865" author="Philippi, RA" journalOrPublisher="INTA, Buenos Aires" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" refId="B35" refString="Philippi, RA, 1860. Florula Atacamensis seu enumeratio plantarum, quas in itinere per desertum Atacamense. Sumptibus E. Anton. https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.162865" title="Florula Atacamensis seu enumeratio plantarum, quas in itinere per desertum Atacamense. Sumptibus E. Anton." url="https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.162865" year="1860">Rudolph A. Philippi (1860)</bibRefCitation>
cited a collection he made near Paposo, Chile. There are two sheets of apparent original material, which agree with the diagnosis and cited locality, at HAL and SGO. Both specimens were presumably studied by Philippi since they were annotated, in his hand, as &quot; 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Eritrichium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eritrichium subamplexicaule" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subamplexicaule">Eritrichium subamplexicaule</taxonomicName>
&quot;. The material at SGO was referred to as the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“type”">&quot;type&quot;</normalizedToken>
of the species name by 
<bibRefCitation author="Johnston, IM" journalOrPublisher="Contributions from the Gray Herbarium of Harvard University" pageId="0" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 118" refId="B16" refString="Johnston, IM, 1927. Studies in the Boraginaceae VI. A revision of the South American Boraginoideae. Contributions from the Gray Herbarium of Harvard University 78: 1 - 118" title="Studies in the Boraginaceae VI. A revision of the South American Boraginoideae." volume="78" year="1927">Johnston (1927)</bibRefCitation>
. Therefore, the element cited by him must be considered as an effective lectotypification.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
